Claims CLAIMS  We claim: 1. A method for separating a nucleic acid from a sample, the method comprising: (a) contacting a sample lysate with a plurality of buoyant, inorganic, nucleic-acid-capture microspheres to form a lysate dispersion; wherein the lysate dispersion comprises a lysate continuous phase and a particulate phase and wherein the particulate phase comprises the plurality of buoyant, inorganic, nucleic-acid-capture microspheres and an adsorbed nucleic acid obtained from the sample; (b) separating the lysate continuous phase from the particulate phase comprising the plurality of buoyant, inorganic, nucleic-acid-capture microspheres and the adsorbed nucleic acid obtained from the sample; and (c) contacting the particulate phase with an eluent to form an eluate comprising the nucleic acid obtained from the sample, wherein the plurality of buoyant, inorganic, nucleic-acid-capture microspheres comprise unicellular hollow microspheres having a diameter between 5 and 300 pm and a true particle density between 0.05 and 0.60 grams/cm 3 . 2. The method of claim 1, wherein the plurality of buoyant inorganic nucleic acid capture microsphere comprise hollow soda-lime-borosilicate microspheres. 3. The method of claim 2, wherein the plurality of buoyant inorganic nucleic acid capture microspheres comprise hollow soda-lime-borosilicate microspheres surrounded by an amorphous silica shell. 4. The method of any one of claims 1-3, wherein the separating step (b) comprises extracting the lysate continuous phase. 5. The method of claim 4, wherein the continuous phase is extracted from a sample collection vessel holding the lysate dispersion by drawing the continuous phase into a pipette or a syringe. 6 The method of claim 5, wherein the pipette or the syringe comprises a microsphere- retaining mesh positioned to prevent the particulate phase from being drawn into a tip of the pipette or a tip of the syringe. 7. The method of any one of claims 1-3, wherein the separating step (b) comprises expelling the lysate continuous phase. 8 The method of claim 7, wherein the lysate continuous phase is expelled from a pipette holding the dispersion or a syringe holding the lysate dispersion. 9. The method of claim 8, wherein the pipette or the syringe comprises a microsphere-retaining mesh positioned to prevent the particulate phase from being expelled from the pipette or the syringe and/or a microsphere-retaining stopper positioned to prevent the particulate phase from being expelled from the pipette or the syringe. 10 The method of any one of claims 1-3, wherein the separating step (b) comprises mechanically separating the lysate continuous phase from the particulate phase. 11. The method of claim 13, wherein the particulate phase is mechanically separated by removing a semi-permeable container positioned within a sample collection vessel holding the dispersion from the sample collection vessel, wherein the semi-permeable container comprises a particle retaining mesh and holds the particulate phase. 12 The method of any one of claims 1-3, wherein the separating step (c) comprises absorbing the particulate phase. 13. The method of claim 12, wherein the particulate phase is adsorbed onto an absorptive pad contacting a meniscus formed of the lysate dispersion. 14. The method of any one of claims 1-13 further comprising: washing the particulate phase with a washing medium; providing the sample lysate; and/or 

 separating the eluate from the plurality of buoyant, inorganic, nucleic-acid-capture microspheres. 15. The method of claim 14, wherein the washing step comprises: contacting the particulate phase, following separation from the lysate continuous phase, with the washing medium to form a washing dispersion, wherein the washing dispersion comprises a washing continuous phase and the particulate phase and separating the washing continuous phase from the particulate phase prior to contacting the particulate phase with the eluent. 16. The method of claim 15, wherein the washing continuous phase is separated from the particulate phase by extracting the washing continuous phase; expelling the washing continuous phase; mechanically separating the washing continuous phase from the particulate phase; or absorbing the particulate phase. 17. The method of claim 14, wherein providing the sample lysate comprises contacting the sample with a lysis or denaturing agent to prepare the sample lysate. 18. The method of any one of claims 1-17, wherein the sample comprises a member of the group consisting of stool, peripheral blood, sera, plasma, ascites, urine, cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), sputum, saliva, bone marrow, synovial fluid, aqueous humor, amniotic fluid, cerumen, breast milk, broncheoalveolar lavage fluid, semen, prostatic fluid, cowper's fluid or pre-ejaculatory fluid, female ejaculate, sweat, fecal matter, hair, tears, cyst fluid, pleural and peritoneal fluid, pericardial fluid, lymph, chyme, chyle, bile, interstitial fluid, menses, pus, sebum, vomit, vaginal secretions, mammary secretions, mucosal secretion, stool, stool water, pancreatic juice, lavage fluids from sinus cavities, bronchopulmonary aspirates, blastocyl cavity fluid, and umbilical cord blood. 19. A method for amplifying a nucleic acid separated from a sample, the method comprising: separating the nucleic acid from the sample according to the method of claim 1; 

 contacting the nucleic acid separated from the sample with an amplification medium; amplifying the nucleic acid separated from the sample. 20 The method of claim 19, wherein the nucleic acid separated from the sample is amplified by a polymerase chain reaction (PCR) technique or an isothermal amplification technique. 21 The method of claim 20, wherein the isothermal amplification technique is selected from Loop-mediated isothermal amplification (LAMP), Reverse-transcriptase loop-mediated isothermal amplification (RT-LAMP), Recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA), Strand displacement amplification (SDA), Helicase-dependent amplification (HDA), Nucleic acid sequence based amplification (NASBA), Nicking enzyme amplification reaction (NEAR), and transcription-mediated amplification (TMA). 22 The method of any one of claims 19-21, wherein the amplification medium comprises a primer complementary to a target sequence indicative of a pathogen or a cell present in the sample. 23. The method of claim 22, wherein the amplification medium comprises a primer complementary to a target sequence indicative of a prokaryotic pathogen, a eukaryotic pathogen, or a viral pathogen. 24. The method of claim 23, wherein the pathogen is a prokaryotic pathogen. 25. The method of claim 23, wherein the pathogen is a eukaryotic pathogen. 26. The method of claim 23, wherein the pathogen is a viral pathogen. 27. The method of any one of claims 19-25, wherein the nucleic acid is separated from the sample according to the method of any one of claims 2-18. 28. A method of detecting a nucleic acid in a sample indicative of a pathogen or a cell, the method comprising: separating the nucleic acid from the sample according to the method of claim 1; contacting the nucleic acid separated from the sample with an amplification medium, wherein the amplification medium comprises a primer complementary to a target sequence indicative of the pathogen or the cell; 

 amplifying the nucleic acid separated from the sample to form an amplified sample comprising a plurality of amplicons of the target sequence; and detecting the target sequence indicative of the pathogen or the cell. 29. The method of claim 28, wherein the detecting step comprises: loading a lateral flow device; and detecting a trimolecular hydridization of (1) the target sequence, (2) a detectably labelled probe specific for the target sequence, and (3) a capture probe for the target sequence; wherein the lateral flow device comprises: a loading area positioned at one end of the lateral flow device, an area comprising the detectably labelled probe specific for a target sequence, wherein said detectably labelled probe is not bound to the lateral flow device and is capable of wicking across at least a portion of the lateral flow device; and an area comprising the capture probe for the target nucleic acid sequence, wherein said capture probe for the target nucleic acid sequence is immobilized on the 1 ateral fl ow devi ce . 30. The method of claim 29, wherein the lateral flow device is loaded with the amplified sample. 31. The method of claim 29, wherein the lateral flow device further comprises an amplification area, the amplification area comprising the amplification medium. 32. The method of claim 31, wherein the lateral flow device is loaded with the eluate. 33. The method of claim 31, wherein the loading area comprises a microsphere loading area. 34. The method of claim 33, wherein the lateral flow device is loaded with the particulate phase. 35. The method of any one of claims 29-34, wherein the lateral flow device is a multiplexed lateral flow device comprising a multiplicity of lateral flow devices. 36. The method of claim 35, wherein the target sequence comprises a multiplicity of target sequences indicative of one or more pathogens and/or one or more cell and wherein the 

 multiplicity of target sequences is less than or equal to the multiplicity of lateral flow devices. 37. The method of claim 36, wherein the multiplicity of target sequences is equal to the multiplicity of lateral flow devices. 38. The method of any one of claims 28-37, wherein the nucleic acid obtained from the sample is amplified by a polymerase chain reaction (PCR) technique or an isothermal amplification technique. 39. The method of claim 38, wherein the isothermal amplification technique is selected from Loop-mediated isothermal amplification (LAMP), Reverse-transcriptase loop-mediated isothermal amplification (RT-LAMP), Recombinase polymerase amplification (RPA), Strand displacement amplification (SDA), Helicase-dependent amplification (HDA), Nucleic acid sequence based amplification (NASBA), Nicking enzyme amplification reaction (NEAR), and transcription-mediated amplification (TMA). 40. The method of any one of claims 28-39, wherein the pathogen is a prokaryotic pathogen, a eukaryotic pathogen, or a viral pathogen. 41. The method of any one of claims 28-39, wherein the cell is a cancer cell. 42. The method of any one of claims 28-41, wherein the nucleic acid is separated from the sample according to the method of any one of claims 2-18. 43. A kit comprising a plurality of buoyant, inorganic, nucleic-acid-capture microspheres and one or more of: (a) a eluent; (b) a lysis or denaturing agent; (c) a washing medium; (d) a amplification medium; (e) a swab; (f) a sample collection vessel; (g) a microsphere separation device; 

 (h) a nucleic acid collection vessel; (i) an amplification device; (j) a testing device; and (k) a control nucleic acid.
